==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[æquidistant]] {{qualifier|archaic}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|équidistant}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|aequidistantem}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|aequi||equal}} + {{m|la|distantem||distant}}.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# occupying a position midway between two ends or sides
# occupying a position that is an equal distance between several [[point]]s. Note that in a one-dimensional space this position can be identified with two points, in a two-dimensional space with three points (not on the same straight line), and in a three-dimensional space with four points (not in the same [[plane]]).
# {{label|en|cartography}} Describing a map [[projection]] that preserves [[scale]]. No map can show scale correctly throughout the entire map but some can show true scale between one or two points and every point or along every [[meridian]] and these are referred to as equidistant.

